<DOC><DOCNO> AP890725-0206 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-89 1924EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Tennis     07-25 0184</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Bush-Tennis,200</SECOND><HEAD>Bush Plays Tennis in Oppressive Heat</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An oppressive heat that has kept manyWashingtonians inside for days did not stop President Bush fromplaying tennis Tuesday.   Bush's enthusiasm to get to the newly resurfaced White Housecourts was undisguised as he stopped to chat with two reporters whospotted him returning to the White House from the Old ExecutiveOffice Building next door.   He raved about the new surface, indicating it had a bouncy feel.   Although it was 90 degrees, and the air was thick with a hazyhumidity, the 65-year-old president said he was off for somedoubles with former Swedish Ambassador Wilhelm Wachtmeister, one ofthe capital's most accomplished tennis players. They were joined bypresidential assistant Roger Porter, head of the Office of PolicyDevelopment and Michael Boskin, chairman of the Council of EconomicAdvisers.   Bush, who also was out on the courts Sunday, said his partnerwould be Wachtmeister.   Looking forward to a future sports opportunity, Bush expressedinterest when the two reporters told him he was invited to play ina softball tournament.</TEXT></DOC>